1. -- {Calculation is an evergreen topic in chess. Improving one's ability to efficiently calculate variations was always considered essential in order to rise the ladder of rankings in the chess world. We can understand the importance of calculation from the fact that improving this skill was discussed right in the early books of chess literature. Consider, for example, the famous book - Think Like a Grandmaster written by Alexander Kotov. This is one of the first books that come to mind. I am sure that if you are a curious student of chess literature you must have surely heard about this book.  Think Like a Grandmaster was one of the first books in which Kotov discussed a systematic approach to raising one's calculation skills. He shared his own experience of how he struggled to calculate even the simplest of variations and focus his mind even when the position lacked complexity. He realized that this was a crucial drawback in his game that he needs to eliminate in order to compete at the highest level. He then formulated a plan for training his calculation, worked on it consistently, and managed to improve his calculation muscle to a great extent. I was lucky to have read this book when I was a young kid! Thanks, coach!  I believe professional players all around the globe took calculation training seriously after this book was released. They set up exercises on the board and solved them without moving pieces as mentioned by Kotov in his book. Then we saw the rise of the World's famous coach and author Mark Dvoretsky. He collected many such exercises for his students in order to train their calculation skills. His method of improving different areas of chess through targeted relevant exercises bore fruits. At one point many of the world's top players were his students! He then went on to publish these exercises in a series of books which were an instant hit!  Let's stop this history class! Let me share my own experience on this subject. In 2013 I was an established International Master with a rating of 2454. I already completed all my Grandmaster norms and was desperately eyeing to cross 2500 and complete my GM title. But I had a huge weakness in my game. No prize for guessing it correctly! Yes, it was my ability to calculate variations. My attention during practice at home was swayed away by the ever-evolving opening theory. It has been almost a year that my results were not as expected and it was evident in my games that my calculation was suffering.   I focused my efforts on strengthening my calculation muscle again. My efforts bore fruits as I completed my GM title a few years later.   Let me share with you how I managed to raise my level in calculation in the next informational.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "FORGET THE THEORY OF CALCULATION AND START SOLVING!"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. -- {From Kotov to Dvoretsky and beyond, numerous authors have made their best efforts to propose a systematic approach to calculating variations.   With all due respect to their contributions, I personally find it challenging to implement them effectively in practical games. Drawing from my experience as both a coach and player, I believe the most effective approach is to develop a few key habits that assist in efficient variation calculation. These habits include:  Exploring a broader range of ideas beyond those initially suggested by your intuition.  Maintaining focus and concentration throughout the calculation process until you reach a definitive conclusion.
Allow me to delve deeper into how we can cultivate these habits.[Habit No. 1 - Exploring Additional Ideas/Finding More Options:]Whenever we observe a position, our brain instinctively begins evaluating it and suggesting a few moves subconsciously. This intuitive 'feeling' helps us gauge whether a particular move appears favorable or unfavorable, and it guides our perception of the correct course of action. While this intuitive feeling or the ideas generated by our intuition serve as valuable signals in strategic positions, it becomes challenging to wholly rely on them in complex situations. Blindly trusting our intuition can prove costly when pieces and pawns are poised for confrontation. In such positions, it is crucial to maintain full concentration and deliberately calculate various variations.  Therefore, when faced with a complex situation on the board, it is advisable to explore the different options available to you from the outset. I have witnessed many of my students placing their trust in their intuition and spending 10-15 minutes deeply calculating a variation, only to realize later that they had been climbing the wrong mountain. Such efforts and precious time on the clock could have been saved by considering multiple ideas at the beginning, before delving deeply into a specific variation. Once we have a shortlist of possible ideas, we can then choose to explore a particular variation in-depth.  As you solve exercises in this course, pose the following question to yourself: What other ideas or options do I have apart from the ones that come easily to mind? Challenge yourself to search for more possibilities. When you consciously seek out options, one of two scenarios is likely to unfold. Firstly, you may discover one or more ideas beyond your initial consideration. If this occurs, ask yourself which of these options seems the most promising. Select that move and commence your calculations. Secondly, you may realize that your initial idea is indeed the best one and that no other viable alternatives are available. In this case, you can proceed with calculating your chosen move. At least you made the effort to explore other options, ensuring that you didn't overlook any hidden resources that may have otherwise eluded you.  [Habit No. 2 - Concentration:]The ability to concentrate and detach ourselves from our surroundings is an important life skill, as evident in elite chess players. Reaching higher levels in chess becomes challenging when our minds are constantly distracted during the game. Therefore, professional chess players must sharpen their concentration skills to utilize them when needed.  Meditation is a timeless practice for improving focus, and I strongly believe that for a chess player, solving chess exercises is akin to meditation. Often, our priority while solving is to find the correct answer to the exercise and discover the best move in the position at any cost. Therefore, when we are unable to achieve that, we feel disheartened. Over the years, I have concluded that solving exercises should also be seen as a means to enhance our focus during the game. In addition to finding the correct answer, we should also assess whether our minds were distracted while solving the position.  A well-known form of meditation involves focusing on our breath. Initially, it may go smoothly for a few seconds or a minute, but as we continue, thoughts start to arise in our minds. This is when we need to redirect our focus back to our breath without becoming annoyed. With consistent practice, a person can increase the span of their focus on their breath and reduce the feeling of irritation when they become lost in thoughts.  The same practice should be applied when solving chess exercises. We set up a position on the board and embark on our quest to find the best move. If the position is challenging and the answer is not immediately apparent, our minds may wander after a few seconds or a minute. We may become carried away by our thoughts. At some point, we become aware of our distraction and may even feel annoyed by its frequency. This sense of irritation can hamper our calculations and negatively impact the rest of the game.  Therefore, when we get distracted while solving challenging positions, it is crucial to refocus our attention on our calculations without irritation or annoyance. If our thoughts wander, we can engage in self-talk and gently bring our attention back to the position in front of us. Through consistent practice of this technique, I was able to significantly improve my concentration, and I encourage you to do the same.  Always keep in mind the two habits we aim to develop through our calculation training in this course. To recap:  A) Challenge yourself to explore more options than those immediately suggested by your intuition, especially in challenging positions.  B) Treat solving challenging positions as a form of meditation. Our objective is not only to find the correct solution but also to enhance our ability to concentrate during the game.  To conclude this introduction, let me offer an analogy. You may have the best products in your company, but without delivery vehicles, it is impossible to deliver them to your customers. Similarly, you may possess exceptional intuition, ideas, and plans in a given position, but without good calculation skills, executing and capitalizing on them may seem insurmountable.  I hope this introduction has effectively conveyed my perspective on chess calculation and its significance. It is now time to open the first chapter of this course. I wish you the best of luck on your journey to improve your calculation skills.} 
