 {White just attacked our Knight with e5, intending to capture it and then mate on g8. Can you find the best move that guarantees a win for Black?} 43. Qa7+ {A)43...Qd4+?44.Kh1Qe4with the same idea as the mainline does not work due to a subtlety.45.Rg1d2and now White escapes with46.Qb3!covering the d1-square. A resource which won't be possible with Black's Queen on b7. The f6-knight is still under attack and Black is forced to opt for a perpetual with46...Rxg2!47.Rxg2Qb1+48.Rg1Qe4+=B)43...Rxf444.Rxf4d2seems like a promising idea for Black. But White escapes here too with the surprising -45.Kf2!A powerful prophylactic move.(45.exf6??with the idea to play Kf2 once Black queens on d1. But this would be a losing blunder since Black has a winning intermezzo,45...Qa7+-+followed by d1-Q when White's King is mated).45...d1=Q46.Qg6+Kh847.exf6=and surprisingly despite having an extra Queen Black won't be able to checkmate White's King.} 
44. Kh1
44. Qb7 {The key idea! By pushing White's King in the corner we ensure that White cannot prevent the mate on g2 by pushing the g-pawn forward.} 
45. Rg1 {45.Rf2covers both the g2-pawn and the d2-square.45...Qe4!46.h3Qe1+47.Kh2Qxf248.hxg4Qxf4+-+Black's Queen gobbles up all White's pawns on the Kingside.} 
45. d2
46. exf6
46. Qxg2+ {The key idea that ensures Black steals the game.} 
47. Rxg2
47. d1=Q+ {With a mate to follow on the next move.} 
