 {White's Pieces are tied down to the c4-Knight which is suffering from an annoying Pin. Can you find the best continuation for Black that would guarantee a decisive advantage.} 27. Nxc4 {There are many interesting ideas for Black, although most of them may appear winning at first glance, White manages to find a way to resist. The main solution, however, is the simplest, shortest, and provides a clear path to achieve a winning advantage. Spotting the correct idea can be quite challenging, even for some Grandmasters. Throughout the years, I have presented this exercise to many of my students, and they have come up with various suggestions for Black. This demonstrates the creative potential of the human mind. I have included their suggestions in the analysis of this exercise.In the game black played,27...Bxc4?28.Bxc4Qa5!?Black demonstrates a strong idea, especially considering she played it with limited time on the clock. The objective is to capture on c4 twice and then win the Bishop on d2. Unfortunately, Black cannot achieve her aims as White employs a spectacular defensive idea, which was discovered in the game. While it initially appears strong, White has a clever defense, which she successfully executed.(28...a5is the engine's suggestion and indeed Black gets good winning chances here.29.Ra4Qd7!the key idea threatening ...Nf3+ followed by Nxd2.30.Kg2Qf7!The Queens come up with another threat. This time eyeing the d5-pawn.31.f3Qc7The third trip for Black's Queen along the 7th Rank. Black now wins material since the 2nd Rank is exposed for White.32.Re1!the only to avoid immediate material losses.(32.Rc1loses the Bishop to32...Nxc433.Rxc4Qxc434.Qxc4Rxc435.Rxc4Re2+-+)32...Rf8↑White's pieces are scattered and Black has a strong initiative).(28...Nf3+leads to nothing after29.Kg2Nxd230.Qxd2Re431.Rc1=)29.Qe4!The only move that saves the game.  A clever defensive resource!(29.Rc1?loses to29...Rxc430.Rxc4Nf3+31.Kg2Nxd2-+)(29.Rd1?is bad too. Black can play29...Qc5!30.Rc1Ng4the f2-pawn is needs immediate care. But after31.Be1Rxe1+32.Rxe1Qxb4-+Black wins)29...Rxc4(The point is that after,29...Nxc430.Rxc4Qxd2?31.Rxc8Rxc8white wins due to,32.Qe6++-)30.Rxc4Qxd231.f4!Nxc432.Qxe8+Bf833.Qe6+Kg734.Qd7+Kh8and now the final precise move35.Qc8!Attacking both Black's bishop and knight prevents Black from creating his own threats and keeps him occupied with defensive moves.35...Qd4+36.Rf2and the game ends in a draw.27...Rxc4?is a direct attempt to win material28.Rxc4Bxc429.Bxc4Qc7unfortunately White has the escaping -30.Qa4=27...Qc7!?This move doesn't directly lead to a tangible advantage for Black, but it certainly puts pressure on White and improves Black's pieces.28.Rc1Qc5∓and White is under tremendous pressure.} 
28. Bxc4
28. Re2 {This is the key hidden idea of this exercise As it turns out that White's Queen is overloaded defending both the bishops!} 
29. Qd1 {29.Rd1?loses to29...Qf8-+or29...Qb6-+} 
29. Rxd2
30. Qxd2
30. Bxc4 {Black possesses two powerful bishops, which puts us in a winning position.} 
