6. Ka1 {A)6.Rxf5White would love to capture this Bishop. But unfortunately Black can force a checkmate!6...Qd1+7.Kb2Rd2+8.Ka3(8.Kc3leads to a quick demise after8...Rc2+9.Kb4Qd6+10.Ka5Rxa2+11.Ba4Qb6)8...Qc1+9.Kb4Re4+!Using all the pieces to hunt down White's King.10.Bd4Now there are a few ways to mate White's King. But for practical purposes, we can simply end the analysis after10...Rexd4+11.exd4Kxg7-+When White can resign.B)6.e4does not change anything at all. Black continues with the same6...Bxe4+7.Ka1Re6-+with a decisive advantage.} 
6. Re6 {The final nail in the coffin. Black's previous moves were strategically aimed at attacking White's f6-Bishop. As you can see, this Bishop is trapped and does not have a safe square along the entire a1-h8 diagonal. With no escape route, the discovered check fails to have any impact. White can only reclaim the Queen with:} 
7. Rg2+
7. Rxf6
8. Rxd2
8. Rxd2 {White won't be able to save the game.} 
