 {White has a pawn less but our pieces are on dominant squares. Find the best continuation for White.} 30. Rd7 {This is by far a superior move than the other two decent alternatives. One of the ideas is to kick the Queen from d5 from where it can perform some defensive functions. Also White can always have the option of intensifying pressure along the 7th Rank by Rbb7.30.R1b6hitting the h6-pawn is a possibility as well. But Black has a few defensive ideas like30...Rd8!which makes it impossible to take on h6. Because after31.Bxh6?Black has31...e4=which simply equalises.30.Rb8is another good option.30...Rf831.Rxf8+Bxf832.Rb8Qd6+-White still maintains good chances but the exchange of a pair of Rooks has benefited Black.} 
30. Qc4 {30...Qe6Offering an exchange of Queens is more tempting. But it is strongly met by,31.Qxe6!fxe631...Rxe632.Rb8+Kh7(32...Bf833.Rdd8+-)33.Rxf7+-when the g7-Bishop is in trouble.32.Rb4+-intending Rg4 which a devastating initiative on the Kingside.} 
31. Rb4 {Another robust punch by White's Rook kicks Black's Queen to the edge of the board on a2. Apart from that, White can now also transfer his Rook to g4 creating dangerous threats. White won the game shortly.} 
